console.log(greet("Sam"));    // "Hello, Sam!"`,caption:"Define once, call many times.",runnable:!0},{type:"explanation",heading:"Parameters and return values",body:"What you pass in (`name`) is called a **parameter**. What comes back out is the **return value**. A function without a `return` returns `undefined` — JavaScript's way of saying 'nothing was given back'."},{type:"walkthrough",title:"Tracing a function call",steps:[{text:'JS sees greet("Aria"). It looks up the function.',highlight:'greet("Aria")'},{text:'It binds the parameter: name = "Aria".',code:'name = "Aria"'},{text:'It runs the body, building "Hello, Aria!"'},{text:"It returns that string. console.log prints it."}]},{type:"challenge",prompt:"Write a function `double` that takes a number and returns it multiplied by 2.",starterCode:`function double(n) {
