score = score + 5;        // change what's in the box
console.log(score);       // 15`,caption:"Use let when the value will change. Use const when it won't.",runnable:!0},{type:"explanation",heading:"let vs const",body:"Use **`const`** by default — it means 'this box stays sealed'. If JavaScript catches you trying to change it, you get an error. That's a *good* thing: it stops bugs.\n\nReach for **`let`** only when you genuinely need to reassign the variable later (a counter, a running total, a moving position)."},{type:"quiz",questions:[{id:"v1",type:"mcq",question:"Which keyword should you use for a value that will never change?",options:["var","let","const","fixed"],correct:2,explanation:"`const` declares a constant — you cannot reassign it after creating it."},{id:"v2",type:"predict-output",question:"What does this code print?",code:`let x = 4;
